\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces (a) DSC mean angular power spectrum (red, with 5-seed $1\sigma $ band) against the rescaled CAMB Planck-2018 best-fit $D_\ell ^{\rm  TT}$ (black) over $\ell \in [2, 2500]$, with reduced $\chi ^2/{\rm  dof} \approx 80$ in the band $\ell \in [30, 256]$. (b) Lattice $D(k) = k^2 P(k)$ from the same simulation; the upper $x$-axis shows the corresponding multipoles under $\ell = 2\pi R_{\rm  shell}\,k$, with the Planck peaks (red dashed) included for reference. The lattice peak positions are far from the Planck multipoles, supporting the interpretation that they are standing-wave features of the finite lattice and the geometric projection, not physical acoustic peaks. Reproducible from \texttt  {notebooks/14\_camb\_benchmark.ipynb}.}}{24}{figure.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:camb_chi2}{{9}{24}{(a) DSC mean angular power spectrum (red, with 5-seed $1\sigma $ band) against the rescaled CAMB Planck-2018 best-fit $D_\ell ^{\rm TT}$ (black) over $\ell \in [2, 2500]$, with reduced $\chi ^2/{\rm dof} \approx 80$ in the band $\ell \in [30, 256]$. (b) Lattice $D(k) = k^2 P(k)$ from the same simulation; the upper $x$-axis shows the corresponding multipoles under $\ell = 2\pi R_{\rm shell}\,k$, with the Planck peaks (red dashed) included for reference. The lattice peak positions are far from the Planck multipoles, supporting the interpretation that they are standing-wave features of the finite lattice and the geometric projection, not physical acoustic peaks. Reproducible from \texttt {notebooks/14\_camb\_benchmark.ipynb}}{figure.9}{}}
\newlabel{fig:camb_chi2@cref}{{[figure][9][]9}{[1][24][]24}}
